# intent (CRON): the housekeeping cron (app/api/cron/housekeeping/route.ts) also
# sweeps stale chat sessions so abandoned conversations (closed without an explicit
# close, or never closed) don't leak files. For each ChatSession older than the
# cutoff it calls deleteSessionFiles(session.id) BEFORE deleting the rows:
#   const stale = await prisma.chatSession.findMany({ where: { updatedAt: { lt: cutoff } } });
#   for (const c of stale) await deleteSessionFiles(c.id);
#   await prisma.chatSession.deleteMany({ where: { id: { in: stale.map(c=>c.id) } } });
# intent (GITIGNORE): add the upload root ("/chat-uploads") to .gitignore so stored
# attachments are never committed.
# intent (TESTS): see section 15 for the full attachment test plan.

# =============================================================================
# 15. TESTS  --  tests/chat.test.ts + tests/chat-attachments.test.ts (bun:test)
# =============================================================================
# intent: unit/integration tests run with `bun test`. Two files; package.json
# scripts: "test:chat" and "test:chat-attachments". Run them SEPARATELY (see the
# mock.module caveat at the end) — each passes on its own (30 and 18 assertions).
#
# HOW THE ROUTES ARE DRIVEN (no server): import the route handlers directly and
# call POST(req)/GET(req, ctx). Requests are built with `new NextRequest(url, {..})`.
#   - JSON send  : body: JSON.stringify(...), header Content-Type: application/json
#   - upload     : body: a FormData with a Blob under "file" (NO Content-Type header)
#   - attachment : GET with ?visitorId=..., ctx = { params: Promise.resolve({ id }) }
# Telegram is exercised for real but `globalThis.fetch` is mocked and branched on
# the URL (/createForumTopic, /getFile, /sendPhoto|sendDocument, the file host).
# Redis is forced off (mock "@/lib/redis" ensureRedis -> null) so pub/sub uses the
# in-memory bus and rate limits use local buckets.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# A. tests/chat.test.ts  (webhook / inbound direction + existing chat behavior)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MOCKS: "@/lib/chat/db" (in-memory), and "@/lib/chat/storage" is STUBBED so the
# webhook path never touches disk — the stub records calls:
#   saveChatFile(sessionId,name,data) -> pushes { sessionId, name, bytes } to
#     `savedFiles` and returns `${sessionId}/${name}`
#   deleteSessionFiles(sessionId)     -> pushes to `deletedSessions`
# The db mock's toMessageDto also maps attachment* -> attachment DTO (so events
# carry attachment metadata).
# CASES (attachment-related):
#   - "ignores messages with neither text nor media"  (renamed; the old wording
#       said "non-text" but media is now handled, so the guard only drops updates
#       with NO text AND NO media).
#   - "deletes stored attachments when the topic is closed"  ( /close -> asserts
#       deletedSessions contains the session id).
#   - "downloads and relays an inbound photo, choosing the largest size": fetch
#       mock returns getFile then raw bytes; asserts one broadcast message with
#       attachment.type==="image", text===caption, savedFiles has 1 entry, and the
#       getFile call used the LARGEST photo's file_id.
#   - "relays an inbound document with its file name and mime": asserts
#       attachment.type==="document", name/mime preserved from the Telegram doc.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# B. tests/chat-attachments.test.ts  (storage + media helpers + upload + serving)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SETUP: process.env.CHAT_UPLOAD_DIR = a fresh os.tmpdir() folder (REAL storage,
# cleaned in afterAll). "@/lib/redis" mocked off. "@/lib/chat/db" is an in-memory
# implementation that is a COMPLETE superset of the module (sessions/messages Maps
# + every exported fn incl. getChatMessageWithSession, closeChatSession, etc.).
# describe "chat storage" (REAL lib/chat/storage):
#   - saveChatFile+readChatFile round-trip (relative path starts with "<sessionId>/").
#   - deleteSessionFiles removes the folder (stat -> not exists).
#   - resolveStoredPath("../../etc/passwd") THROWS (traversal guard).
#   - attachmentTypeFromMime image/video/audio/pdf -> image/video/audio/document.
#   - clientAttachmentsEnabled(): true by default, false only for "false".
# describe "telegram media helpers" (REAL telegram, fetch mocked):
#   - extractMedia picks the largest photo size; documents ok; null for plain text.
#   - getTelegramFile resolves file_path; downloadTelegramFile hits the FILE host
#       URL (/file/bot<token>/<path>); sendMediaToTopic posts to /sendPhoto with a
#       FormData body.
# describe "chat send route: uploads" (REAL send route, storage, telegram; db mock):
#   - 403 when NEXT_PUBLIC_LIVE_CHAT_ATTACHMENTS_ENABLED="false" (server-side gate).
#   - 400 when no file part.
#   - image upload: 200, returned message has attachment DTO (type/name), text is
#       the caption, errorText undefined, AND the bytes are readable from disk via
#       the persisted attachmentPath.
#   - Telegram failure (mock sendDocument ok:false): still 200, attachment persisted
#       with errorText containing the Telegram description ("store-first" contract).
# describe "chat attachment endpoint" (REAL GET + storage; db mock):
#   - owner visitorId -> 200, Content-Type image/png, Content-Disposition inline,
#       bytes match.
#   - ?download=1 -> Content-Disposition attachment.
#   - different visitorId -> 403;  missing visitorId -> 400.
#
# CAVEAT (why run files separately): bun's mock.module is PROCESS-GLOBAL, so if both
# files run in one `bun test` invocation their differing "@/lib/chat/db" and
# "@/lib/chat/storage" mocks collide. Keep each file's mocks a COMPLETE superset of
# the module's exports (the in-memory db mock here defines ALL functions for that
# reason) OR run the two files in separate processes (the npm scripts do).

# =============================================================================
# BUGS FIXED IN THIS PASS (for changelog/reference)
# =============================================================================
# [FOCUS-STEAL] The open/focus effect listed `resetChat` in its deps, and
#   `resetChat` was memoized with [name, email]. Every keystroke in the intake
#   fields recreated resetChat -> re-ran the effect -> a 300ms timer re-focused
#   the message textarea, yanking the caret out of name/email. FIX: resetChat is
#   now [] (reads name/email via refs) and the effect focuses name-vs-textarea
#   based on which is mounted.
# [REFRESH-RESET] visitorId + open state were persisted in sessionStorage and
#   restored on mount (with an empty id that never reconnected the SSE stream).
#   FIX: identity lives only in memory (visitorIdRef), so a window refresh always
#   yields a fresh session and the restore-with-empty-id path is gone.
# [BUBBLE-CLOSE] The floating bubble called setIsOpen(o=>!o) and discarded an
#   active session with no confirmation. FIX: while open it calls handleClose(),
#   which shows the confirm modal for a live session (matching the header X).
# [SSE-BUFFERING] Telegram replies were persisted, published (subscriberCount:1),
#   received by the stream handler, and enqueued — the server logs proved every
#   step — yet the browser EventSource never fired its "message" listener. Cause:
#   the SSE response was being buffered/compressed so live frames were held until
#   the stream ended. FIX: add `Cache-Control: no-cache, no-transform` and
#   `X-Accel-Buffering: no` to the /api/chat/stream response so each frame flushes
#   immediately (see section 4).
# [REDIS-RESUB] After a Redis disconnect/reconnect, the dedicated subscriber could
#   silently stop receiving on channels that were subscribed before the first
#   "ready" event (ioredis autoResubscribe edge case), so messages published after
#   a blip never reached the stream. FIX: handleReconnect explicitly re-subscribes
#   to every tracked channel; publish logs subscriberCount for diagnosis (section 6).
# [SSE-LEAK] Only cancel() cleaned up, but a real browser disconnect aborts
#   req.signal instead of calling cancel(), leaking a Redis subscriber + intervals
#   on every page reload. FIX: shared cleanup() wired to both cancel() and
#   req.signal "abort" (section 4).
# [CLUSTER-INMEM-PUBSUB] The in-memory pub/sub bus is PROCESS-LOCAL, so under PM2
#   cluster (exec_mode "cluster", instances "max") a Telegram webhook landing on
#   worker A published to A's memory bus while the visitor's SSE stream on worker
#   B was subscribed only to B's memory bus — the reply was SILENTLY LOST. The
#   stream only started DB polling `if (!unsubscribe)`, but subscribeChatEvents
#   returns the (truthy) memory unsubscribe when Redis is down, so polling never
#   engaged. FIX (section 4): start polling whenever the transport is not DURABLE
#   — `durableTransport = Boolean(unsubscribe) && isRedisReady()`; if false,
#   startPolling(). Also added checkSessionStatus() to the poll (re-reads session
#   status and synthesizes the `closed` event once) so a cross-worker close still
#   reaches the client when Redis is unavailable. Redis remains REQUIRED for
#   real-time cross-worker delivery; polling is the durable degraded path. The
#   in-memory REGISTRY has no DB fallback, so multi-worker /start sharing requires
#   Redis (degrades gracefully to the env chat-id fallback, not an outage).

# =============================================================================
# FEATURES ADDED (for changelog/reference)
# =============================================================================
# [RICH-ATTACHMENTS] Bidirectional file support (image/video/audio/voice/document),
#   ON BY DEFAULT. Visitor uploads go multipart -> stored on disk (per-session
#   folder keyed on ChatSession.id) -> relayed to Telegram; agent media is
#   getFile+downloaded -> stored -> streamed to the visitor. The SSE payload carries
#   only metadata; bytes are served by an authenticated GET route that authorizes on
#   the per-conversation visitorId and switches inline vs download disposition.
#   Storage is fronted by a traversal guard, gated by a server-enforced flag
#   (NEXT_PUBLIC_LIVE_CHAT_ATTACHMENTS_ENABLED), size-capped (CHAT_MAX_UPLOAD_MB),
#   and reclaimed on every close path + a housekeeping-cron sweep so no orphaned
#   files survive. See sections 1,2,3,5,7,8,9,12,13,14. KEY DECISIONS: (1) metadata
#   on the message row, bytes off-DB; (2) store-before-relay so a Telegram failure
#   never hides the visitor's own upload (recorded via errorText instead); (3) paths
#   keyed on the stable session id, never the rotating visitorId; (4) the client
#   flag is presentational only — the server re-checks the same predicate.
# [MULTI-GROUP-ROUND-ROBIN] The single hardcoded TELEGRAM_SUPPORT_CHAT_ID is now a
#   FALLBACK. Support groups register themselves at runtime via chat commands and
#   new visitor chats are distributed round-robin across them. Each session still
#   gets its OWN forum topic inside the chosen group (so telegramThreadId stays
#   unique and session resolution is unchanged). Also: leaving the chat in the
#   frontend now closes the Telegram forum topic. See section 15 below.
#   KEY DECISIONS: (1) round-robin unit is the GROUP (chatId); per-session topics
#   are unchanged. (2) A Redis registry (chat:groups hash + chat:groups:cursor +
#   chat:groups:initialized) is authoritative once ANY group runs /start; before
#   that the env chat id is the fallback; after init an empty list DISABLES chat.
#   (3) Commands are group-level and handled BEFORE session lookup in the webhook;
#   /close remains per-session. (4) send/media helpers gained an optional
#   targetChatId (env fallback) so existing call sites + tests are unchanged.
#   (5) In-memory fallback mirrors the attachment/pubsub pattern when Redis is off.

# =============================================================================
# 15. MULTI-GROUP ROUND-ROBIN DISPATCH + TOPIC CLOSE-ON-LEAVE
# =============================================================================
# intent: turn the one-group model into a self-service pool of Telegram support
# groups that admins manage with in-chat commands, distribute new conversations
# round-robin, and mirror a frontend "leave" into a Telegram topic close.
#
# --- lib/chat/registry.ts (NEW) --------------------------------------------
# Redis-backed round-robin registry with a single-process in-memory fallback.
# KEYS: chat:groups (hash chatId->JSON{title,paused,registeredAt}),
#       chat:groups:cursor (INCR per dispatch), chat:groups:initialized ("1").
#   registerGroup(chatId,title?)  -> HSET (unpauses, preserves registeredAt) +
#                                     set initialized=1. First call overrides env.
#   pauseGroup(chatId)            -> mark paused (kept in list, skipped for new).
#   removeGroup(chatId)           -> HDEL.
#   listGroups()/getGroup(id)     -> read.
#   canDispatch()                 -> PEEK: any non-paused group? else if never
#                                     initialized fall back to TELEGRAM_SUPPORT_CHAT_ID;
#                                     else false (empty/all-paused => disabled).
#   selectDispatchChatId()        -> CONSUME: stable-sort active by
#                                     (registeredAt,chatId), pick cursor%len (INCR),
#                                     else env fallback (pre-init), else {disabled}.
#   resetRegistryForTests()       -> clears in-memory state for suite isolation.
#
# --- lib/chat/telegram.ts (CHANGED) ----------------------------------------
#   createForumTopic(name, targetChatId?)            } targetChatId defaults to
#   sendMessageToTopic(text, threadId, targetChatId?, options?)  } getSupportChatId()
#   sendMediaToTopic(threadId, media, targetChatId?) } (env) — back-compatible.
#   + sendPlainMessage(chatId, text, threadId?)  -> command replies (HTML).
#   + closeForumTopic(chatId, threadId)          -> Telegram closeForumTopic.
#   + parseGroupCommand(text): "start"|"pause"|"end"|null — strips @mention,
#       case-insensitive, trims; returns null for /close and everything else.
#   TelegramMessage.chat gains optional `title` (used to label a registered group).
#
# --- app/api/chat/telegram/route.ts (CHANGED) ------------------------------
#   After isBotMessage and BEFORE session lookup: parseGroupCommand(text); if set,
#   handleGroupCommand(cmd, message) (operates on message.chat.id, replies in the
#   same thread), always acks 200:
#     start -> registerGroup(chatId, chat.title); reply active-group count.
#     pause -> pauseGroup(chatId); reply (or hint to /start if unregistered).
#     end   -> for each open session in the group: closeChatSession +
#              deleteSessionFiles + closeForumTopic + publish status:closed;
#              then removeGroup(chatId); reply (note "disabled" when list empty).
#   The per-session /close path additionally calls closeForumTopic when the agent
#   typed /close (skipped when forum_topic_closed already closed it).
#
# --- app/api/chat/send/route.ts (CHANGED) ----------------------------------
#   ensureTopic() now: selectDispatchChatId() -> throw CHAT_DISABLED if disabled,
#   else createForumTopic(name, target.chatId) and record chatId+thread on the
#   session. Before creating a topic for a NEW session, both handleText and
#   handleUpload return 403 "Live chat is currently unavailable." when
#   !canDispatch(). Outbound sends pass session.telegramChatId as targetChatId so
#   replies route to the SAME group the topic lives in.
#
# --- app/api/chat/close/route.ts (CHANGED) ---------------------------------
#   After marking closed + deleting files, best-effort closeForumTopic(
#   telegramChatId, telegramThreadId) so a frontend "leave" ends the Telegram
#   topic too (failure is logged, never fails the visitor's close).
#
# --- app/api/chat/config/route.ts (NEW) ------------------------------------
#   GET -> { enabled: NEXT_PUBLIC_LIVE_CHAT_ENABLED!=="false" && await canDispatch() }.
#   Rate-limited by the new "chat.config" bucket. On registry error, falls back to
#   the env flag (a Redis blip must not hide the widget).
#
# --- components/LiveChat.tsx (CHANGED) -------------------------------------
#   On mount, fetch /api/chat/config -> serverEnabled (default true). Render guard:
#   `if (!enabled) return null; if (!serverEnabled && !session) return null;` so the
#   launcher hides when no group accepts chats, but an in-progress session (held in
#   memory) is never yanked away.
#
# --- lib/chat/db.ts (CHANGED) ----------------------------------------------
#   + listOpenChatSessionsByChatId(telegramChatId): open sessions in a group (for /end).
#
# --- db mock note ----------------------------------------------------------
#   tests/chat.test.ts's "@/lib/chat/db" mock must also export
#   listOpenChatSessionsByChatId (the webhook now imports it at module load).
#
# --- tests/chat-registry.test.ts (NEW) -------------------------------------
#   Redis mocked off (in-memory). parseGroupCommand table + round-robin lifecycle:
#   env fallback pre-init -> register A,B -> A,B,A,B -> pause A -> B only (still
#   listed) -> re-register A unpauses -> remove all -> disabled even with env set.
#   Calls resetRegistryForTests() up front + in afterAll for cross-file isolation.
